{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778976812787,"sessionID":"ses_1ccb84d98ffeWH3ShOq9EHPmcq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"call_q6O2lK9jFDoPOIWVs0IcqRki","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"jq -r '.body, (.comments[] | \"---COMMENT---\\n\" + .author.login + \"\\n\" + .body)' __issue_context__.json","timeout":120000,"workdir":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon","description":"Prints full imported issue context"},"output":"**Preferred term label:**\nparotid gland ducto-acinar\n\n**Synonyms**\n\n**Definition (free text, please give PubMed ID)**\nEaster QT, et al. Single-cell and spatially resolved interactomics of tooth-associated keratinocytes in periodontitis. Nat Commun. 2024 Jun 14;15(1):5016. doi: 10.1038/s41467-024-49037-y. PMID: 38876998; PMCID: PMC11178863; https://doi.org/10.48539/HBM632.GTVR.643\n\n**Parent term (use https://www.ebi.ac.uk/ols/ontologies/uberon)**\nUBERON:0001831  parotid gland\n\n**Your nano-attribution (ORCID)**\n0000-0002-2999-0103\n\n---------------\n**Preferred term label:**\ngingival attachment\n\n**Synonyms**\n\n**Definition (free text, please give PubMed ID)**\nEaster QT, et al. Single-cell and spatially resolved interactomics of tooth-associated keratinocytes in periodontitis. Nat Commun. 2024 Jun 14;15(1):5016. doi: 10.1038/s41467-024-49037-y. PMID: 38876998; PMCID: PMC11178863; https://doi.org/10.48539/HBM632.GTVR.643\n\n**Parent term (use https://www.ebi.ac.uk/ols/ontologies/uberon)**\nUBERON:0001828  gingiva\n\n**Your nano-attribution (ORCID)**\n0000-0002-2999-0103\n\n---------------\n**Preferred term label:**\nsublingual gland ducto-acinar\n\n**Synonyms**\n\n**Definition (free text, please give PubMed ID)**\nEaster QT, et al. Single-cell and spatially resolved interactomics of tooth-associated keratinocytes in periodontitis. Nat Commun. 2024 Jun 14;15(1):5016. doi: 10.1038/s41467-024-49037-y. PMID: 38876998; PMCID: PMC11178863; https://doi.org/10.48539/HBM632.GTVR.643\n\n**Parent term (use https://www.ebi.ac.uk/ols/ontologies/uberon)**\nUBERON:0001832  sublingual gland\n\n**Your nano-attribution (ORCID)**\n0000-0002-2999-0103\n\n---------------\n**Preferred term label:**\nsubmandibular gland ducto-acinar\n\n**Synonyms**\n\n**Definition (free text, please give PubMed ID)**\nEaster QT, et al. Single-cell and spatially resolved interactomics of tooth-associated keratinocytes in periodontitis. Nat Commun. 2024 Jun 14;15(1):5016. doi: 10.1038/s41467-024-49037-y. PMID: 38876998; PMCID: PMC11178863; https://doi.org/10.48539/HBM632.GTVR.643\n\n**Parent term (use https://www.ebi.ac.uk/ols/ontologies/uberon)**\nUBERON:0001736  submandibular gland\n\n**Your nano-attribution (ORCID)**\n0000-0002-2999-0103\n\nrelated issue: https://github.com/obophenotype/cell-ontology/issues/3471\n---COMMENT---\ncmungall\n@dragon-ai-agent please analyze these terms, provide a plan for how you will add them to the ontology, check for existing naming conventions and design patterns for similar terms\n---COMMENT---\ndragon-ai-agent\n## Analysis of Term Requests\n\nI've analyzed the four term requests and the reference publication. Here's my plan for adding these terms to the ontology:\n\n### **Terms Requested:**\n1. **parotid gland ducto-acinar** (parent: UBERON:0001831 parotid gland)\n2. **gingival attachment** (parent: UBERON:0001828 gingiva)\n3. **sublingual gland ducto-acinar** (parent: UBERON:0001832 sublingual gland)\n4. **submandibular gland ducto-acinar** (parent: UBERON:0001736 submandibular gland)\n\n### **Key Findings:**\n\n#### 1. **Existing Ontology Coverage**\n- All three salivary glands (parotid, sublingual, submandibular) are well-represented in UBERON\n- Each has associated ducts, epithelium, mesenchyme, and developmental terms\n- Gingiva (UBERON:0001828) exists with several subclasses including gingival epithelium\n- **No existing \"ducto-acinar\" or \"acinar\" substructure terms** for salivary glands found\n\n#### 2. **Reference Publication Context**\n- PMID:38876998 (Easter et al., Nature Communications 2024) is titled \"Single-cell and spatially resolved interactomics of tooth-associated keratinocytes in periodontitis\"\n- The paper focuses on periodontitis and tooth-associated keratinocytes using single-cell RNA sequencing\n- While cited for all terms, this paper is primarily about gingival/periodontal biology rather than salivary gland anatomy\n\n#### 3. **Anatomical Background - Ducto-Acinar Structures**\nBased on salivary gland anatomy literature:\n- Salivary glands have a fundamental **acinar-ductal unit** structure\n- Acini are secretory end pieces that produce saliva\n- The ductal system includes intercalated, striated, and excretory ducts\n- \"Ducto-acinar\" likely refers to the integrated functional unit of ducts and acini\n\n#### 4. **Design Pattern Considerations**\n\n**Option A: Compositional Pattern (part_of)**\n- Create terms like \"ducto-acinar unit\" as anatomical structures\n- Use intersection_of with part_of relationships\n- Example: intersection_of: UBERON:XXXXXX ! ducto-acinar unit + intersection_of: part_of UBERON:0001831 ! parotid gland\n\n**Option B: Generic \"ducto-acinar\" parent class**\n- Create a single parent term \"salivary gland ducto-acinar unit\"\n- Make gland-specific terms subclasses with part_of relationships\n\n**Option C: Match existing gland substructure patterns**\n- The ontology has epithelium, duct, mesenchyme terms for each gland\n- Add \"ducto-acinar unit\" following the same compositional pattern\n\n### **Questions & Concerns:**\n\n1. **Terminology Clarification Needed:**\n   - Is \"ducto-acinar\" referring to:\n     a) The combined acinar-ductal functional unit?\n     b) A specific region where acini meet ducts?\n     c) A cell population identified in the scRNA-seq study?\n\n2. **Gingival Attachment:**\n   - This term needs special attention - in periodontal anatomy, \"gingival attachment\" typically refers to **junctional epithelium** and the **epithelial attachment** to the tooth surface\n   - The ontology already has UBERON:0001949 (gingival epithelium)\n   - Need to clarify if this refers to:\n     a) The junctional epithelium specifically?\n     b) A broader concept including connective tissue attachment?\n     c) The entire attachment apparatus?\n\n3. **Citation Appropriateness:**\n   - PMID:38876998 is about periodontitis and keratinocytes, not specifically about ducto-acinar anatomy\n   - Should we seek additional anatomical references for proper definitions?\n\n### **Recommended Next Steps:**\n\n1. **Clarify terminology** with the requester (@zhengj2007) regarding:\n   - Precise anatomical definition of \"ducto-acinar\" in this context\n   - Whether these terms represent anatomical structures or cell populations from the scRNA-seq study\n   - Clarification on \"gingival attachment\" - is this junctional epithelium?\n\n2. **Additional literature review** for:\n   - Standard anatomical definitions of ducto-acinar structures\n   - Additional PMIDs specifically about salivary gland anatomy\n\n3. **Check with HubMap** - Given the HBM dataset reference in the issue, these may be atlas-specific terms needed for data annotation\n\n4. **Design pattern decision** - Once terminology is clarified, choose appropriate pattern (likely Option C for consistency)\n\nWould you like me to proceed with clarifying questions to the requester, or do you have specific guidance on how these terms should be modeled?\n\n@dragon-ai-agent\n---COMMENT---\nzhengj2007\n\n@dragon-ai-agent please address:\n\nHere are the answers to your questions and concerns:\n\n1. We are defining the “ducto-acinar” FTU as the combined acinar–ductal functional unit of human salivary glands (option \"a\")_. Specifically, this refers to the structural-functional module composed of secretory acini together with their contiguous ductal segments (intercalated and striated ducts, and proximal collecting ducts where applicable). Importantly, this FTU is not limited to epithelial components alone. Our definition includes the associated stromal and vascular microenvironment that supports secretion, modification, and transport. In other words, this is a multicellular functional tissue unit.\n--This definition aligns with the HRA concept of FTUs as repeating structural-functional modules that integrate epithelial, stromal, and vascular compartments. It is not intended to denote a specific transitional anatomical interface (acini–duct junction only) nor a transcriptomically defined cell population. These terms are intended for human anatomy only and are being anchored to HRA spatial coordinates. \n\nWe need \"ducto-acinar\" added in uberon. In classic literature, the ducto-acinar unit is sometimes called the \"salivon\" -- think of it relative to a hydrangea plant. The ductoacinar unit or salivon is one bulb and a stem. The salivary gland is the entire plant. Separating duct and acinar in this case would be like separating the flowers from their woody stem before connecting the branches that eventually connect to the main stem and then roots. \n\n2. For the gingival attachment term, the intended meaning corresponds to the entire dentogingival/periodontal attachment apparatus. Thus, among the proposed options, the closest answer is (c): the entire attachment apparatus. We agree that “gingival attachment” can be ambiguous in periodontal anatomy. If helpful for ontology precision, we would support renaming or clarifying the label to reflect that this represents a multi-tissue anatomical complex rather than gingival epithelium alone (which is already represented by UBERON:0001949). As with the ducto-acinar FTU, this unit includes stromal and vascular components as part of the functional microenvironment and is being defined in the context of human anatomy for HRA spatial anchoring.\n\n3.  You are correct that PMID:38876998 is not appropriate as a primary anatomical reference for glands -- I would use [https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0