va, connected to a ductal system that modifies this fluid. \nThe associated reference is:\nhttps://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538325/\n---COMMENT---\ndragon-ai-agent\n## Proposed Parent Term and Definitions for Salivary Gland Ducto-Acinar Units\n\n@zhengj2007 Thank you for the detailed clarifications! Based on the information you provided and my review of the UBERON ontology structure, here is my proposal.\n\n---\n\n### Background: Ontological Modeling\n\nI reviewed analogous structures in UBERON for guidance:\n- **Mammary gland lobule** (UBERON:0001912): `is_a lobule` (UBERON:0009911), `part_of mammary gland`, contains both secretory alveoli and lactiferous ducts\n- **Liver lobule** (UBERON:0004647): `is_a organ part`, `part_of liver parenchyma`  \n- **Nephron** (UBERON:0001285): the functional unit of the kidney, `is_a organ part`, `part_of uriniferous tubule`\n\nThe ducto-acinar unit (salivon) is the direct salivary gland equivalent of the mammary gland lobule: a repeating functional module within the gland that integrates both secretory (acinar) and ductal compartments, together with supportive stromal and vascular elements. I therefore propose it be modeled similarly as `is_a lobule` (UBERON:0009911).\n\n---\n\n### Proposed Term Hierarchy\n\n#### Generic parent term (NEW):\n\n**Label:** salivary gland ducto-acinar unit  \n**Synonym (EXACT):** salivon  \n**Synonym (RELATED):** salivary gland ducto-acinar  \n**is_a:** UBERON:0009911 ! lobule  \n**part_of:** UBERON:0001044 ! saliva-secreting gland  \n**Definition:**  \n> \"A lobule of a salivary gland consisting of secretory acini together with their contiguous ductal segments, including the intercalated duct and striated duct, together with associated myoepithelial cells, stromal tissue, and vasculature. This structural-functional unit is responsible for the production of primary saliva by the acinar cells and its ionic modification during transit through the ductal segments.\" [PMID:24862590, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538325/]\n\n**Comment:** Also known as the \"salivon\" in classical salivary physiology literature. The three major salivary glands (parotid, submandibular, sublingual) contain gland-specific variants of this unit that differ in acinar cell composition (serous vs. mucous vs. mixed).\n\n---\n\n#### Gland-specific terms (NEW):\n\n**1. parotid gland ducto-acinar unit**  \n**Label:** parotid gland ducto-acinar unit  \n**Synonym (RELATED):** parotid gland ducto-acinar  \n**is_a:** salivary gland ducto-acinar unit (new term above)  \n**part_of:** UBERON:0001831 ! parotid gland  \n**Definition:**  \n> \"A salivary gland ducto-acinar unit that is part of the parotid gland, consisting of purely serous acini together with their contiguous intercalated and striated ductal segments, and associated myoepithelial cells, stromal tissue, and vasculature. This unit produces a watery, protein-rich serous saliva.\" [PMID:24862590, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538325/]\n\n---\n\n**2. sublingual gland ducto-acinar unit**  \n**Label:** sublingual gland ducto-acinar unit  \n**Synonym (RELATED):** sublingual gland ducto-acinar  \n**is_a:** salivary gland ducto-acinar unit (new term above)  \n**part_of:** UBERON:0001832 ! sublingual gland  \n**Definition:**  \n> \"A salivary gland ducto-acinar unit that is part of the sublingual gland, consisting of predominantly mucous acini (with minor serous demilunes) together with their contiguous ductal segments, and associated myoepithelial cells, stromal tissue, and vasculature. This unit produces a viscous, mucin-rich saliva.\" [PMID:24862590, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538325/]\n\n---\n\n**3. submandibular gland ducto-acinar unit**  \n**Label:** submandibular gland ducto-acinar unit  \n**Synonym (RELATED):** submandibular gland ducto-acinar  \n**is_a:** salivary gland ducto-acinar unit (new term above)  \n**part_of:** UBERON:0001736 ! submandibular gland  \n**Definition:**  \n> \"A salivary gland ducto-acinar unit that is part of the submandibular gland, consisting of a mixture of predominantly serous acini (approximately 90%) with a minority of mucous acini, together with their contiguous ductal segments, and associated myoepithelial cells, stromal tissue, and vasculature. This unit produces a mixed serous-mucous saliva.\" [PMID:24862590, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538325/]\n\n---\n\n### Notes and Questions\n\n1. **Label format:** I am proposing to use \"ducto-acinar unit\" rather than just \"ducto-acinar\" as the label, since this makes it clear we are defining an anatomical structure (a unit), not an adjective. The requested names (\"parotid gland ducto-acinar\" etc.) would be included as RELATED synonyms. Does this naming work for HRA data annotation purposes?\n\n2. **References:** For salivary gland-specific ducto-acinar composition, I used:\n   - PMID:24862590 (Holmberg & Hoffman 2014, *Monogr Oral Sci* - salivary gland anatomy/biogenesis)\n   - https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538325/ (StatPearls: Anatomy, Salivary Glands)\n   - The HBM dataset DOI (https://doi.org/10.48539/HBM632.GTVR.643) can be added as an xref\n   \n3. **Stromal/vascular components:** The text definitions above mention stroma and vasculature, consistent with the FTU definition you provided. However, for the OWL logical definition, I would keep the intersection_of axioms simpler (acinus + ductal parts). Should we explicitly add has_part relationships for stroma and vasculature?\n\n4. **Taxon scope:** Since these are intended for human anatomy (HRA), should we add `in_taxon NCBITaxon:9606` constraints, or keep them broader for potential cross-species use?\n\nPlease let me know if these definitions and parent terms are satisfactory, and I will proceed to add these terms to the ontology.\n\n@dragon-ai-agent\n---COMMENT---\nzhengj2007\n@dragon-ai-agent please propose UBERON parent term and definition of \"gingival attachment\" based on the information I provided:\n\nYou have questions about the term \"gingival attachment\".\nThe response from HRA domain experts are:\nFor the gingival attachment term, the intended meaning corresponds to the entire dentogingival/periodontal attachment apparatus. Thus, among the proposed options, the closest answer is (c): the entire attachment apparatus. We agree that “gingival attachment” can be ambiguous in periodontal anatomy. If helpful for ontology precision, we would support renaming or clarifying the label to reflect that this represents a multi-tissue anatomical complex rather than gingival epithelium alone (which is already represented by UBERON:0001949). \n\nAdditionally, I obtained the following information via a Google search:\nAttached gingiva is the firm, resilient, keratinized gum tissue bound directly to the underlying alveolar bone and cementum, extending from the free gingiva to the mucogingival junction. \nAssociated references:\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3532730/\nhttps://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3462203/\n\n\n---COMMENT---\ndragon-ai-agent\n## Proposed Parent Term and Definition for \"Gingival Attachment\"\n\n@zhengj2007 Thank you for the clarifications and additional references. After reviewing the existing UBERON terms and the provided references, here is my analysis and proposal.\n\n---\n\n### Important Terminological Distinction\n\nBefore proposing a definition, I need to flag a key ambiguity in the information provided:\n\nThe HRA domain experts stated that the intended concept is **option (c): the entire dentogingival/periodontal attachment apparatus** (junctional epithelium + connective tissue attachment + cementum surface).\n\nHowever, the Google search results and the references provided describe a **different concept**: **\"attached gingiva\"** — the firm, keratinized portion of the gingiva tightly bound to alveolar bone and cementum, delimited coronally by the free gingival groove and apically by the mucogingival junction.\n\nThe two PMC/PMID references provided:\n- **PMC3532730** (Wennström et al. study): explicitly about width of **attached gingiva**\n- **PMID:3462203** (Benson et al.): about reformation of the **supracrestal attachment unit** after crown placement — a third concept relating to the biologic width\n\nThese references do not describe the \"entire dentogingival/periodontal attachment apparatus\" as described by the HRA experts.\n\n---\n\n### Existing UBERON Terms to Be Aware Of\n\n| UBERON ID | Name | Notes |\n|-----------|------|-------|\n| UBERON:0001828 | gingiva | The parent term; fibrous investing tissue with keratinized epithelium surrounding a tooth |\n| UBERON:0001949 | gingival epithelium | Stratified squamous epithelium of the gingiva (part_of gingiva) |\n| UBERON:0035149 | **gingival epithelial attachment** | Anatomical junction; part_of gingival epithelium; located_in gingival groove |\n| UBERON:0001758 | periodontium | The entire tooth-supporting apparatus (PDL + gingivae + cementum + alveolar bone) |\n| UBERON:0035967 | alveolar mucosa | \"The mucous membrane **apical to the attached gingiva**\" — already references the concept |\n\nNote: **UBERON:0035149 (gingival epithelial attachment)** already exists and captures the junctional/epithelial attachment component. The full \"attachment apparatus\" would approximate **UBERON:0001758 (periodontium)**.\n\n---\n\n### Proposed Term: **attached gingiva**\n\nBased on the provided references (PMC3532730, PMID:3462203) and the context in UBERON (alveolar mucosa is defined as apical to the attached gingiva), I propose:\n\n**Label:** attached gingiva  \n**Synonym (RELATED):** gingival attachment  \n**is_a:** UBERON:0001828 ! gingiva  \n**Definition:**  \n> \"The firm, resilient, keratinized portion of the gingiva that is tightly bound to the underlying periosteum of the alveolar bone and cementum, extending from the free gingival groove (or base of the gingival sulcus) coronally to the mucogingival junction apically. This region is continuous with but distinct from the free gingiva and from the alveolar mucosa apical to the mucogingival junction.\" [PMID:3462203, https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3532730/]\n\n**Comment:** The width of the attached gingiva varies by tooth position. This term is distinct from UBERON:0035149 (gingival epithelial attachment), which refers specifically to the epithelial junction at the base of the gingival sulcus. \n\n**Logical definition:**  \n\n\n---\n\n### Alternative Interpretation: Dentogingival Junction\n\nIf the intended concept truly is the **entire dentogingival/periodontal attachment apparatus** (as stated by HRA experts), then a different term would be more appropriate:\n\n**Label:** dentogingival junction  \n**is_a:** UBERON:0007651 ! anatomical junction  \n**part_of:** UBERON:0001758 ! periodontium  \n**Definition:**  \n> \"The multi-tissue complex that anchors the gingival tissue to the tooth surface, comprising the junctional epithelium, the supracrestal connective tissue attachment, and the cementum surface to which fibers attach, together with associated vasculature and stromal tissue.\"\n\nHowever, this concept significantly overlaps with existing terms (periodontium, gingival epithelial attachment), and I am not convinced there is sufficient distinction to warrant a separate UBERON term.\n\n---\n\n### My Recommendation\n\nI recommend **Option A (\"attached gingiva\")** as it:\n1. Is well-supported by the two references provided\n2. Fills a genuine gap in UBERON (alveolar mucosa already references this concept)\n3. Is clearly distinct from existing terms\n4. Fits naturally under the gingiva parent (UBERON:0001828) as requested\n\n**However, could you please confirm:**\n1. Is \"attached gingiva\" (the keratinized zone between free gingival groove and mucogingival junction) the intended concept for HRA spatial annotation?\n2. Or is the intent to represent the entire attachment apparatus (junctional epithelium + connective tissue), which would warrant a different term and parent?\n\nThis clarification is needed because the references you provided describe \"attached gingiva\" while the HRA expert description describes the broader attachment apparatus.\n\n@dragon-ai-agent\n---COMMENT---\nnicolevasilevsky\nI will work on this @zhengj2007 (we discussed this on an HRA call)\n---COMMENT---\nzhengj2007\n@dragon-ai-agent please propose UBERON parent term and definition of \"gingival attachment\" again.\n\nYou have questions about the term \"gingival attachment\".\nThe response from HRA domain experts are:\nFor the gingival attachment term, the intended meaning corresponds to the entire dentogingival/periodontal attachment apparatus. Thus, among the proposed options, the closest answer is (c): the entire attachment apparatus. We agree that “gingival attachment” can be ambiguous in periodontal anatomy. If helpful for ontology precision, we would support renaming or clarifying the label to reflect that this represents a multi-tissue anatomical complex rather than gingival epithelium alone (which is already represented by UBERON:0001949).\n---COMMENT---\ndragon-ai-agent\n## Revised Proposal for \\\"gingival attachment\\\"\n\n@zhengj2007 Thank you for clarifying. Given the confirmed intent — **the entire dentogingival/periodontal attachment apparatus, a multi-tissue complex** — here is my revised proposal.\n\n---\n\n### Context: What's already in UBERON\n\n| UBERON ID | Name | Notes |\n|-----------|------|-------|\n| UBERON:0001828 | gingiva | Fibrous investing tissue with keratinized epithelium surrounding a tooth; the requested parent |\n| UBERON:0001758 | periodontium | Broader: PDL + gingivae + cementum + alveolar bone |\n| UBERON:0001949 | gingival epithelium | Stratified squamous epithelium of the gingiva |\n| UBERON:0035149 | gingival epithelial attachment | Only the epithelial component; is_a anatomical junction, part_of gingival epithelium |\n\nNo existing UBERON term captures the **full multi-tissue attachment complex** (epithelium + connective tissue + vasculature/stroma) anchoring the gingiva to the tooth.\n\n---\n\n### Proposed New Term\n\n**Preferred label:** dentogingival junction  \n**Synonym (RELATED):** gingival attachment  \n**Synonym (RELATED):** dentogingival complex  \n**Synonym (RELATED):** supracrestal tissue attachment  \n\n**is_a:** UBERON:0000479 ! tissue  \n**part_of:** UBERON:0001828 ! gingiva  \n\n**Proposed definition:**\n> \\\"A multi-tissue anatomical complex that constitutes the attachment zone between the gingival tissue and the tooth surface, comprising the junctional epithelium, the supracrestal connective tissue attachment fibers, and supporting stromal and vascular elements. This structure seals the periodontal space from the oral cavity and serves as the primary physical and biological interface anchoring the free and attached gingiva to the tooth.\\\" [PMID:38876998, ISBN:9780323096300]\n\n(ISBN:9780323096300 = Ten Cate's Oral Histology, 8th ed., which describes the dentogingival junction in detail)\n\n---\n\n### Rationale for label choice\n\nI propose **\\\"dentogingival junction\\\"** as the preferred label because:\n1. It is the standard anatomical term in Ten Cate's Oral Histology and Schroeder's Periodontium\n2. It avoids ambiguity — \\\"gingival attachment\\\" in the literature is often used inconsistently (sometimes meaning only the junctional epithelium, sometimes the attached gingiva zone)\n3. \\\"Gingival attachment\\\" is preserved as a RELATED synonym so HRA annotation can use it\n\nIf you prefer \\\"gingival attachment\\\" as the primary label, that is also acceptable — please confirm.\n\n---\n\n### Distinguishes from existing terms\n\n- **UBERON:0035149 (gingival epithelial attachment):** Only the epithelial junction component; the proposed term is broader, including connective tissue and vasculature\n- **UBERON:0001949 (gingival epithelium):** The epithelial layer of the gingiva (not the attachment complex)\n- **UBERON:0001758 (periodontium):** Broader — includes periodontal ligament, cementum, and alveolar bone; the proposed term is restricted to the gingival attachment zone\n\n---\n\n### Question\n\nPlease confirm:\n1. Is **\\\"dentogingival junction\\\"** acceptable as the preferred label, with \\\"gingival attachment\\\" as RELATED synonym? Or should \\\"gingival attachment\\\" be the preferred label?\n2. Should I proceed with adding this term to the ontology, or await further input from @nicolevasilevsky?\n\n@dragon-ai-agent\n---COMMENT---\nzhengj2007\nHi @nicolevasilevsky Based on chatting with @dragon-ai-agent (previous comments), here are proposed terms with definitions. I highlighted our original requested term labels in bold font. \n\nGeneric parent term **ducto-acinar** (NEW, added for 3 terms needed by HuBMAP):\nLabel: salivary gland ducto-acinar unit\nSynonym (EXACT): salivon\nSynonym (RELATED): salivary gland ducto-acinar\nis_a: UBERON:0009911 ! lobule\npart_of: UBERON:0001044 ! saliva-secreting gland\nDefinition:\n\n\"A lobule of a salivary gland consisting of secretory acini together with their contiguous ductal segments, including the intercalated duct and striated duct, together with associated myoepithelial cells, stromal tissue, and vasculature. This structural-functional unit is responsible for the production of primary saliva by the acinar cells and its ionic modification during transit through the ductal segments.\" [PMID:24862590, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538325/]\nComment: Also known as the \"salivon\" in classical salivary physiology literature. The three major salivary glands (parotid, submandibular, sublingual) contain gland-specific variants of this unit that differ in acinar cell composition (serous vs. mucous vs. mixed).\n\n3 terms as children of \"salivary gland ducto-acinar unit\" (**ducto-acinar**) requested by Griffin:\n\n1. parotid gland ducto-acinar unit (**parotid gland ducto-acinar**)\nLabel: parotid gland ducto-acinar unit\nSynonym (RELATED): parotid gl