ave specific guidance on how these terms should be modeled?\n\n@dragon-ai-agent\n---COMMENT---\nzhengj2007\n\n@dragon-ai-agent please address:\n\nHere are the answers to your questions and concerns:\n\n1. We are defining the “ducto-acinar” FTU as the combined acinar–ductal functional unit of human salivary glands (option \"a\")_. Specifically, this refers to the structural-functional module composed of secretory acini together with their contiguous ductal segments (intercalated and striated ducts, and proximal collecting ducts where applicable). Importantly, this FTU is not limited to epithelial components alone. Our definition includes the associated stromal and vascular microenvironment that supports secretion, modification, and transport. In other words, this is a multicellular functional tissue unit.\n--This definition aligns with the HRA concept of FTUs as repeating structural-functional modules that integrate epithelial, stromal, and vascular compartments. It is not intended to denote a specific transitional anatomical interface (acini–duct junction only) nor a transcriptomically defined cell population. These terms are intended for human anatomy only and are being anchored to HRA spatial coordinates. \n\nWe need \"ducto-acinar\" added in uberon. In classic literature, the ducto-acinar unit is sometimes called the \"salivon\" -- think of it relative to a hydrangea plant. The ductoacinar unit or salivon is one bulb and a stem. The salivary gland is the entire plant. Separating duct and acinar in this case would be like separating the flowers from their woody stem before connecting the branches that eventually connect to the main stem and then roots. \n\n2. For the gingival attachment term, the intended meaning corresponds to the entire dentogingival/periodontal attachment apparatus. Thus, among the proposed options, the closest answer is (c): the entire attachment apparatus. We agree that “gingival attachment” can be ambiguous in periodontal anatomy. If helpful