n\nBased on the provided references (PMC3532730, PMID:3462203) and the context in UBERON (alveolar mucosa is defined as apical to the attached gingiva), I propose:\n\n**Label:** attached gingiva  \n**Synonym (RELATED):** gingival attachment  \n**is_a:** UBERON:0001828 ! gingiva  \n**Definition:**  \n> \"The firm, resilient, keratinized portion of the gingiva that is tightly bound to the underlying periosteum of the alveolar bone and cementum, extending from the free gingival groove (or base of the gingival sulcus) coronally to the mucogingival junction apically. This region is continuous with but distinct from the free gingiva and from the alveolar mucosa apical to the mucogingival junction.\" [PMID:3462203, https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3532730/]\n\n**Comment:** The width of the attached gingiva varies by tooth position. This term is distinct from UBERON:0035149 (gingival epithelial attachment), which refers specifically to the epithelial junction at the base of the gingival sulcus. \n\n**Logical definition:**  \n\n\n---\n\n### Alternative Interpretation: Dentogingival Junction\n\nIf the intended concept truly is the **entire dentogingival/periodontal attachment apparatus** (as stated by HRA experts), then a different term would be more appropriate:\n\n**Label:** dentogingival junction  \n**is_a:** UBERON:0007651 ! anatomical junction  \n**part_of:** UBERON:0001758 ! periodontium  \n**Definition:**  \n> \"The multi-tissue complex that anchors the gingival tissue to the tooth surface, comprising the junctional epithelium, the supracrestal connective tissue attachment, and the cementum surface to which fibers attach, together with associated vasculature and stromal tissue.\"\n\nHowever, this concept significantly overlaps with existing terms (periodontium, gingival epithelial attachment), and I am not convinced there is sufficient distinction to warrant a separate UBERON term.\n\n---\n\n### My Recommendation\n\nI recommend **Option A (\"attached gingiva\")