 in UBERON\n\n| UBERON ID | Name | Notes |\n|-----------|------|-------|\n| UBERON:0001828 | gingiva | Fibrous investing tissue with keratinized epithelium surrounding a tooth; the requested parent |\n| UBERON:0001758 | periodontium | Broader: PDL + gingivae + cementum + alveolar bone |\n| UBERON:0001949 | gingival epithelium | Stratified squamous epithelium of the gingiva |\n| UBERON:0035149 | gingival epithelial attachment | Only the epithelial component; is_a anatomical junction, part_of gingival epithelium |\n\nNo existing UBERON term captures the **full multi-tissue attachment complex** (epithelium + connective tissue + vasculature/stroma) anchoring the gingiva to the tooth.\n\n---\n\n### Proposed New Term\n\n**Preferred label:** dentogingival junction  \n**Synonym (RELATED):** gingival attachment  \n**Synonym (RELATED):** dentogingival complex  \n**Synonym (RELATED):** supracrestal tissue attachment  \n\n**is_a:** UBERON:0000479 ! tissue  \n**part_of:** UBERON:0001828 ! gingiva  \n\n**Proposed definition:**\n> \\\"A multi-tissue anatomical complex that constitutes the attachment zone between the gingival tissue and the tooth surface, comprising the junctional epithelium, the supracrestal connective tissue attachment fibers, and supporting stromal and vascular elements. This structure seals the periodontal space from the oral cavity and serves as the primary physical and biological interface anchoring the free and attached gingiva to the tooth.\\\" [PMID:38876998, ISBN:9780323096300]\n\n(ISBN:9780323096300 = Ten Cate's Oral Histology, 8th ed., which describes the dentogingival junction in detail)\n\n---\n\n### Rationale for label choice\n\nI propose **\\\"dentogingival junction\\\"** as the preferred label because:\n1. It is the standard anatomical term in Ten Cate's Oral Histology and Schroeder's Periodontium\n2. It avoids ambiguity — \\\"gingival attachment\\\" in the literature is often used inconsistently (sometimes meaning only the junctional epithelium, sometimes the attached gingiva zone)\n3. \\\"Gingival attachment\\\" is preserved as a RELATED synonym so HRA annotation can use it\n\nIf you prefer \\\"gingival attachment\\\" as the primary label, that is also acceptable — please confirm.\n\n---\n\n### Distinguishes from existing terms\n\n- **UBERON:0035149 (gingival epithelial attachment):** Only the epithelial junction component; the proposed term is broader, including connective tissue and vasculature\n- **UBERON:0001949 (gingival epithelium):** The epithelial layer of the gingiva (not the attachment complex)\n- **UBERON:0001758 (periodontium):** Broader — includes periodontal ligament, cementum, and alveolar bone; the proposed term is restricted to the gingival attachment zone\n\n---\n\n### Question\n\nPlease confirm:\n1. Is **\\\"dentogingival junction\\\"** acceptable as the preferred label, with \\\"gingival attachment\\\" as RELATED synonym? Or should \\\"gingival attachment\\\" be the preferred label?\n2. Should I proceed with adding this term to the ontology, or await further input from @nicolevasilevsky?\n\n@dragon-ai-agent\n---COMMENT---\nzhengj2007\nHi @nicolevasilevsky Based on chatting with @dragon-ai-agent (previous comments), here are proposed terms with definitions. I highlighted our original requested term labels in bold font. \n\nGeneric parent term **ducto-acinar** (NEW, added for 3 terms needed by HuBMAP):\nLabel: salivary gland ducto-acinar unit\nSynonym (EXACT): salivon\nSynonym (RELATED): salivary gland ducto-acinar\nis_a: UBERON:0009911 ! lobule\npart_of: UBERON:0001044 ! saliva-secreting gland\nDefinition:\n\n\"A lobule of a salivary gland consisting of secretory acini together with their contiguous ductal segments, including the intercalated duct and striated duct, together with associated myoepithelial cells, stromal tissue, and vasculature. This structural-functional unit is responsible for the production of primary saliva by the acinar cells and its ionic modification during transit through the ductal segments.\" [PMID:24862590, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538325/]\nComment: Also known as the \"salivon\" in classical salivary physiology literature. The three major salivary glands (parotid, submandibular, sublingual) contain gland-specific variants of this unit that differ in acinar cell composition (serous vs. mucous vs. mixed).\n\n3 terms as children of \"salivary gland ducto-acinar unit\" (**ducto-acinar**) requested by Griffin:\n\n1. parotid gland ducto-acinar unit (**parotid gland ducto-acinar**)\nLabel: parotid gland ducto-acinar unit\nSynonym (RELATED): parotid gland ducto-acinar\nis_a: salivary gland ducto-acinar unit (new term above)\npart_of: UBERON:0001831 ! parotid gland\nDefinition:\n\n\"A salivary gland ducto-acinar unit that is part of the parotid gland, consisting of purely serous acini together with their contiguous intercalated and striated ductal segments, and associated myoepithelial cells, stromal tissue, and vasculature. This unit produces a watery, protein-rich serous saliva.\" [PMID:24862590, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538325/]\n\n2. sublingual gland ducto-acinar unit (**sublingual gland ducto-acinar**)\nLabel: sublingual gland ducto-acinar unit\nSynonym (RELATED): sublingual gland ducto-acinar\nis_a: salivary gland ducto-acinar unit (new term above)\npart_of: UBERON:0001832 ! sublingual gland\nDefinition:\n\n\"A salivary gland ducto-acinar unit that is part of the sublingual gland, consisting of predominantly mucous acini (with minor serous demilunes) together with their contiguous ductal segments, and associated myoepithelial cells, stromal tissue, and vasculature. This unit produces a viscous, mucin-rich saliva.\" [PMID:24862590, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538325/]\n\n3. submandibular gland ducto-acinar unit (**submandibular gland ducto-acinar**)\nLabel: submandibular gland ducto-acinar unit\nSynonym (RELATED): submandibular gland ducto-acinar\nis_a: salivary gland ducto-acinar unit (new term above)\npart_of: UBERON:0001736 ! submandibular gland\nDefinition:\n\n\"A salivary gland ducto-acinar unit that is part of the submandibular gland, consisting of a mixture of predominantly serous acini (approximately 90%) with a minority of mucous acini, together with their contiguous ductal segments, and associated myoepithelial cells, stromal tissue, and vasculature. This unit produces a mixed serous-mucous saliva.\" [PMID:24862590, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538325/]\n\n**gingival attachment**\nPreferred label: dentogingival junction\nSynonym (RELATED): gingival attachment\nSynonym (RELATED): dentogingival complex\nSynonym (RELATED): supracrestal tissue attachment\n\nis_a: UBERON:0000479 ! tissue\npart_of: UBERON:0001828 ! gingiva\n\nProposed definition:\n\n\"A multi-tissue anatomical complex that constitutes the attachment zone between the gingival tissue and the tooth surface, comprising the junctional epithelium, the supracrestal connective tissue attachment fibers, and supporting stromal and vascular elements. This structure seals the periodontal space from the oral cavity and serves as the primary physical and biological interface anchoring the free and attached gingiva to the tooth.\" [PMID:38876998, ISBN:9780323096300]\n(ISBN:9780323096300 = Ten Cate's Oral Histology, 8th ed., which describes the dentogingival junction in detail)\n\nAll terms are intended for human anatomy (HRA), we may consider adding in_taxon NCBITaxon:9606 constraints.\n\nCould you please review the labels and definitions and contact @cmungall for what the next step? Thanks!\n\n","exit":0,"description":"Prints full imported issue context","truncated":false},"title":"Prints full imported issue context","time":{"start":1778976812772,"end":1778976812782}},"id":"prt_e3347e92e001cUeUmWK92gQf2c","sessionID":"ses_1ccb84d98ffeWH3ShOq9EHPmcq","messageID":"msg_e3347d8eb001qsqCxdt2viRP1Q"}}
